---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";

const abstracts = [
  {
    duration: "45 min · talk",
    title: "Specs are the new source code",
    body: `Everyone can get an AI agent to write code. Far fewer can get agents to ship software that survives production. This talk lays out the operating system I use to do exactly that: specs as the source of truth agents work against, a zero-tolerance CI that treats every warning as an error, mechanical guards that catch the mistakes agents reliably make, and human gates where judgment actually matters. Drawing on Kaiord — an open-source platform written entirely by agents and released as 9 npm packages — I show how these pieces fit together, where they fail, and how the human role shifts from writing code to designing the system that lets agents write it safely.`,
  },
  {
    duration: "30 min · talk",
    title: "Evals as CI: making stochastic systems boring",
    body: `"It worked when I tried it" is not a quality bar for LLM features. This talk turns evaluation into engineering. Using Kaiord's open-source evals harness as a running case study, I walk through 22 domain benchmarks, the assertions that grade each response, and the 90% pass gate that blocks a merge in CI when quality regresses. We cover how to choose a threshold you can defend, how to write assertions that catch real failures without flaking, and how to fold evals into the same pipeline as your tests. You leave with a concrete, copyable pattern for treating model quality as a build artifact — measurable, versioned, and enforced — instead of a vibe.`,
  },
  {
    duration: "25 min · talk",
    title: "GEO: making your product discoverable to AI agents",
    body: `Search is no longer the only front door — increasingly, AI agents decide what to recommend. Generative Engine Optimization (GEO) is how you make your product legible to them. This talk covers the concrete surface area: llms.txt as a machine-readable map of your site, structured data and JSON-LD that state facts unambiguously, and the registries — like the official MCP registry — where agents actually look. I use a single-day GEO program I ran on Kaiord as the worked example: what shipped, what moved, and what didn't. You leave knowing which signals are worth the effort, which are cargo-cult, and how to instrument discoverability so you can tell the difference with data.`,
  },
];

const proof = [
  { label: "kaiord.com", href: "https://kaiord.com" },
  { label: "GitHub — pablo-albaladejo", href: "https://github.com/pablo-albaladejo" },
  {
    label: "MCP registry entry",
    href: "https://registry.modelcontextprotocol.io/v0.1/servers?search=io.github.pablo-albaladejo/kaiord",
  },
  { label: "Writing — evals, agentic dev, observability", href: "/blog" },
];

const label = "font-mono text-[15px] font-semibold tracking-[0.08em] text-faint";
const subLabel = "font-mono text-[12px] tracking-[0.08em] text-faint";

// Mirrors the home Person entity so the speaker page carries the same
// machine-readable identity engines use to reconcile the name.
const speakerJsonLd = JSON.stringify({
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "ProfilePage",
  mainEntity: {
    "@type": "Person",
    name: "Pablo Albaladejo",
    url: "https://pabloalbaladejo.com/",
    jobTitle: "AI Engineer",
    description:
      "Speaker on shipping production software with AI agents, LLM evaluation, and GEO. Talks in English and Spanish.",
    knowsAbout: [
      "AI agents",
      "LLM evaluation",
      "LLM observability",
      "RAG",
      "AI infrastructure",
      "AWS",
      "TypeScript",
      "Production AI systems",
    ],
    sameAs: [
      "https://github.com/pablo-albaladejo",
      "https://linkedin.com/in/pabloalbaladejomestre",
      "https://stackoverflow.com/users/3395884/pablo-albaladejo",
      "https://dev.to/pabloalbaladejo",
      "https://kaiord.com",
      "https://deepgent.net",
    ],
  },
});
---

<Base
  title="Talks — Pablo Albaladejo"
  description="Pablo Albaladejo, AI Engineer — talks on shipping software with AI agents, LLM evals in production, and GEO. English & Spanish, Madrid-based."
  lang="en"
  path="/talks"
  active="talks"
  ogImage="/og/talks.png"
>
  <script
    type="application/ld+json"
    set:html={speakerJsonLd}
    slot="head"
  />
  <main class="mx-auto max-w-[70ch] pt-16 pb-24 min-[700px]:pt-[88px]">
    <h1
      class="mb-6 text-[38px] leading-[1.1] font-bold tracking-[-0.02em] text-pretty min-[700px]:text-[48px]"
    >
      Talks
    </h1>
    <p class="text-[19px] leading-[1.7] text-body text-pretty">
      Available for technical talks in English and Spanish. Based in Madrid,
      remote-friendly. I speak about building production software with AI
      agents, evaluating LLMs in production, and making products discoverable
      to AI agents — every claim anchored to public, verifiable artifacts.
    </p>

    <section class="mt-20">
      <h2 class={label}>BIO</h2>

      <p class:list={[subLabel, "mt-8 mb-2"]}>SHORT</p>
      <p class="text-[16px] leading-[1.7] text-body text-pretty">
        Pablo Albaladejo is an AI Engineer — production LLM systems, agents
        &amp; infrastructure. At Aircall his systems process 1M+ call
        transcriptions a day. He created Kaiord,
        an open-source, local-first training platform written entirely by AI
        agents — 9 packages on npm, listed in the official MCP registry. With
        17+ years in SaaS, he writes and speaks about agentic development, LLM
        evals, and observability.
      </p>

      <p class:list={[subLabel, "mt-7 mb-2"]}>LONG</p>
      <p class="text-[16px] leading-[1.7] text-body text-pretty">
        Pablo Albaladejo is an AI Engineer — production LLM systems, agents
        &amp; infrastructure. At Aircall in Madrid his systems process more
        than a million call
        transcriptions a day. Across 17+ years in SaaS he has shipped
        production backends on AWS and TypeScript, and now focuses on building
        software with AI agents end to end. He is the creator of Kaiord, an
        open-source, local-first training platform where every line of code
        was written by AI agents. Kaiord ships as 9 packages on npm —
        including an SDK, a CLI, and an MCP server — and is listed in the
        official Model Context Protocol registry; its evals harness runs 22
        benchmarks behind a 90% quality gate in CI. Pablo writes and speaks
        about agentic development, evaluating LLMs in production, and
        observability for AI pipelines. Every claim in his talks is anchored
        to public, verifiable artifacts — code, PRs, and docs. He speaks in
        English and Spanish and is remote-friendly.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-20">
      <h2 class={label}>ABSTRACTS</h2>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-5">
        {
          abstracts.map((talk, i) => (
            <article class="rounded-xl border border-line bg-surface p-7">
              <p class="mb-3 flex items-center gap-3 font-mono text-[12.5px] text-faint">
                <span class="text-accent">{String(i + 1).padStart(2, "0")}</span>
                <span>{talk.duration}</span>
              </p>
              <h3 class="text-[23px] font-bold tracking-[-0.01em] text-ink text-pretty">
                {talk.title}
              </h3>
              <p class="mt-3 text-[16px] leading-[1.65] text-body text-pretty">
                {talk.body}
              </p>
            </article>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-20">
      <h2 class={label}>PROOF</h2>
      <p class="mt-4 text-[16px] leading-[1.65] text-body">
        Every claim above is verifiable on these properties.
      </p>
      <ul class="mt-5 grid gap-3">
        {
          proof.map((item) => (
            <li>
              <a
                href={item.href}
                class="font-mono text-[14px] text-accent no-underline hover:underline"
              >
                → {item.label}
              </a>
            </li>
          ))
        }
      </ul>
    </section>

    <section class="mt-20">
      <div
        class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-between gap-6 rounded-[14px] bg-ink p-10 text-paper"
      >
        <div class="max-w-[36ch]">
          <h2 class="text-[26px] font-bold tracking-[-0.01em]">
            Invite me to speak
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-2 text-[16px] leading-[1.6] text-paper/70">
            Organizing a meetup, conference, or internal session? A line about
            your audience and format is enough to start.
          </p>
        </div>
        <a
          href="https://linkedin.com/in/pabloalbaladejomestre"
          data-email="pablo.albaladejo.mestre"
          data-domain="gmail.com"
          data-subject="Talk invitation"
          class="rounded-lg bg-accent-br px-6 py-4 font-mono text-[14px] text-white no-underline hover:opacity-90"
          >Invite me →</a
        >
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</Base>
